The ILCR due to the five emission sources for adults and children throughout the year was calculated by combining the emissions from different sources, as shown in Fig.  5 . For adults, combustion sources, such as biomass, natural gas, and coal, had the largest impact (4.2 × 10 –6 ), representing about 46.7% of the total, followed by industrial emission sources (4.0 × 10 –6 ), which accounted for 45.2% of the total, and finally petrol and diesel combustion sources (7.1 × 10 –7 ), which accounted for about 8% of the total. The impact of the five sources on children throughout the year was close to that for adults, with fossil fuel combustion sources being the highest ILCR (2.0 × 10 –6 ), corresponding to 47.1% of the total, followed by industrial emissions (1.9 × 10 –6 ), corresponding to about 45% of the total, and finally petrol and diesel combustion sources (3.3 × 10 –7 ) at about 7.8%. Over the year, the ILCR from combustion emissions, such as coal burning and industrial emissions, was relatively high. Therefore, the authorities should take measures to control exposure to PAHs from combustion sources and industrial emissions to reduce the health risks to adults and children. Figure 5 Annual health risks from five PAH sources for children and adults.

